<span class="displaytext"><b><em>"our nation cannot afford the (PARTY NAME) and a (PARTY NAME) president like (candidate full) who will sign tax increases into law. instead of following (PARTY NAME), we need to lower taxes, cut spending, and grow the economy."</em> – gov. (candidate full)</b> (gov. (candidate full), press release, 10/25/07) <p align="center"> <b>the (candidate last) vision: "the right answer is always to keep taxes down"</b> </p><p><b> <u>gov. (candidate last) rejects the (PARTY NAME)' attempts to raise taxes on american families:</u> </b> </p><p><b>gov. (candidate last) believes that america "can't afford" the (PARTY NAME)' plans to increase taxes.</b> gov. (candidate last): "charlie rangel just came out this week saying he wants to put a surcharge on taxes, largest increase in the history of america. look, more taxes are what the (PARTY NAME) have in mind to fund many of (candidate full)'s million good ideas. we can't afford that. it would slow down the economy. it would kill job creation in this country." (cnbc's "mad money," 10/28/07) </p><p><b>gov. (candidate last): "the right answer is always to keep taxes down."</b> gov. (candidate last): "the right answer is always to keep taxes down. don't add new taxes, but instead allow the american people and the entrepreneurial spirit to grow our economy. that's the best way to get revenues for government and the best ways to get good jobs for our people." (cnbc's "mad money," 10/28/07) </p><p><b>gov. (candidate last) opposes the (PARTY NAME)' plans to roll back the bush tax cuts.</b> gov. (candidate last): "let me tell you what i'd do, as opposed to what (candidate full) would do with regard to our tax and spending policies. first of all, i would make the bush tax cuts permanent immediately – all of them, not some of them, but all of them." (gov. (candidate full), remarks to the club for growth, 10/17/07) </p><p><b> <u>gov. (candidate last) does not support raising taxes to fix social security:</u> </b> </p><p><b>gov. (candidate last) believes that raising taxes to bail out social security is "the wrong way to go."</b> (candidate last): "for people 20 and 30 and 40 years old, we have four major options, for instance, for social security. one is the one (PARTY NAME) want: raise taxes. it's the wrong way to go." (fox news, (PARTY NAME) presidential candidate debate, orlando, fl, 10/21/07) </p><p align="center"> <b>the (PARTY NAME): call tax increases "fair"</b> </p><p><b> <u>the (PARTY NAME) support raising taxes on american families:</u> </b> </p><p><b>sen. (candidate full) (d-ny) said that rolling back the bush tax cuts will be "more fair."</b> (candidate last): "that's why i put fiscal responsibility first, because we have to change the bush tax cuts, which i am committed to doing. we have to move back toward a more fair and progressive tax system and begin once again to move <br/>toward a balanced budget with a surplus." (nbc's (PARTY NAME) presidential candidate debate at drexel university, philadelphia, pa, 10/30/07) </p><blockquote dir="ltr" style="margin-right: 0px"> <p>- <b>sen. (candidate last): "let's start taking the tax cuts away from the wealthy."</b> (nbc's (PARTY NAME) presidential candidate debate at drexel university, philadelphia, pa, 10/30/07) </p></blockquote> <p><b>sen. (candidate last) supports a "freeze" on the death tax.</b> (candidate last): "and there are a lot of moving pieces here. you know, there are kinds of issues we're going to deal with as the tax cuts expire. i want to freeze the estate tax at the 2009 level of 7 million (dollars) for a couple." (nbc's (PARTY NAME) presidential candidate debate at drexel university, philadelphia, pa, 10/30/07) </p><p><b>sen. (candidate full) (d-il) said that rolling back the bush tax cuts "simply restores some fairness."</b> (candidate last): "those kinds of progressive tax steps, while closing loopholes and rolling back the bush tax cuts to the top 1 percent, simply restores some fairness and a sense that we're all in this together as opposed to each of us being in it on our own." (nbc's (PARTY NAME) presidential candidate debate at drexel university, philadelphia, pa, 10/30/07) </p><p><b>sen. (candidate last) would raise the cap on social security payroll taxes.</b> (candidate last): "i think the best way to approach this is to adjust the cap on the payroll tax so that people like myself are paying a little bit more and people who are in need are protected. that is the option that i will be pushing forward." (nbc's "meet the press," 11/11/07) </p><blockquote dir="ltr" style="margin-right: 0px"> <p><b>- sen. (candidate last) even supports a tax increase on himself.</b> nbc's tim russert: "a tax increase for some?" (candidate last): "tax increase for people like myself probably." (nbc's "meet the press," 11/11/07) </p></blockquote> <p><b>sen. (candidate last) wants americans to pay "a little bit more," even "middle class folks."</b> (candidate last): "so what i've said -- and i know some others on this stage have said -- is that among the options that are available, the best one is to lift the cap on the payroll tax, potentially exempting folks in the middle -- middle-class folks -- but making sure that the wealthy are paying more of their fair share, a little bit more." (nbc's (PARTY NAME) presidential candidate debate at drexel university, philadelphia, pa, 10/30/07)</p></span>



